INFORMATION_SOURCE: IGM Chile Report: 31_Parra_Baez_Chilean_part_of_SIRGAS.pdf on sirgas.org website (www.sirgas.org website national networks list shows 269 passive and 13 continuous stations in this network whereas IGM Chile source document cites 650 stations).

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: ITRF2000 at epoch 2005.8.  Network of 34 GPS stations throughout the country, five of which were connected to four Caribbean area ITRF stations.
REMARKS: Replaces Ocotepeque (datum code 1070) in Costa Rica from March 2007.

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: ITRF2005 at epoch 2010.14.
DATUM_SCOPE: Engineering survey and construction of Fehmarnbelt tunnel.
REMARKS: Defined through coordinates of four permanant GNSS stations.

DATUM_SCOPE: Engineering survey and construction of Fehmarnbelt tunnel.

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of LAT by specifying location and epoch, for instance "LAT at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: Defined by transformation from ETRS89 (transformation code 5826) to be an average of DHDN across all states of Germany.
INFORMATION_SOURCE: Deutsche Bahn AG via Geo++, www.geopp.de

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The highest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of HAT by specifying location and epoch, for instance "HAT at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average of the lowest low waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of LLWLT by specifying location and epoch, for instance "LLWLT at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average of the highest high waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of HHWLT by specifying location and epoch, for instance "HHWLT at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The level below MSL equal to the sum of the amplitudes of the harmonic constituents M2, S2, K1 and O1. It approximates mean lower low water spring tides (MLLWS).
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of ISLW by specifying location and epoch, for instance "ISLW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

DATUM_NAME: Mean Lower Low Water Spring Tides
ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the lower low water spring tides at a place.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MLLWS by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MLLWS at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the low waters of spring tides.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MLWS by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MLWS at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the high waters of spring tides.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MHWS by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MHWS at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the lower low waters at a place over a 19-year period.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MLLW by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MLLW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the higher high waters at a place over a 19-year period.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MHHW by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MHHW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of all low waters at a place over a 19-year period.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MLW by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MLW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The average height of the high waters at a place over a 19-year period.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of MHW by specifying location and epoch, for instance "MHW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The lowest level reached by the water surface in one tidal cycle. When used in inland (non-tidal) waters it is generally defined as a level which the daily mean water level would fall below less than 5% of the time.
DATUM_SCOPE: Hydrography and Nautical Charting, mostly in harbour and river engineering.
REMARKS: On a river it is a sloping surface. Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of low water by specifying location and epoch, for instance "Low water at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".

ORIGIN_DESCRIPTION: The highest level reached at a place by the water surface in one tidal cycle. When used on inland (non-tidal) waters it is generally defined as a level which the daily mean water level exceeds less than 5% of the time.
DATUM_SCOPE: Hydrography and Nautical Charting, mostly in harbour and river engineering.
REMARKS: Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realisations of high water by specifying location and epoch, for instance "High water at xxx during yyyy-yyyy".
